Many places are saved on disinfection agents
More than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to incorrect handling of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions in hospitals, the overlap of beds, the overload of staff - all factors that are not just affordable to remove infections, says the chief doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, the disinfection agents are also saved.
In the traumatology department of János Hospital, a MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria was found in a male patient who was entered into hospital after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but shortly later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important surgery could not be carried out since then because of the bacteria still in the patient's body.
By December 10th of this year, the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System was reported from hospitals in 1094 by multi-resistant pathogens caused infections, Karolina Böröcz, the chief doctor of the National Epidemiology Center, said.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals with certainty, but the dark numbers are likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacyllin.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria carries about one-third of people in their nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, almond inflammation, skin inflammation or wounds) react usually well to antibiotics, they are well healed.
However, if the agents are dosed too highly or applied incorrectly, antibiotic-resistant bacteria will arise from the well-responding bacteria that quickly spread in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakening, or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in older, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the daily life of the disease.
You cannot confuse the infection with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA there is only not where it is not searched for.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the caregivers wear rubber gloves and masks in care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Although patients are examined for MRSA, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Samplings too rare
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, though the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable to prevent the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant agent, says Karolina Börökz.
After this infection mainly occurs in hospitals and age homes, the hospitals should investigate the patients involved and immediately isolate MRSA-infected.
However, microbiological sampling is not so frequently practiced in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the state’s health insurance system for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore come to the daylight until the patient has already a notable MRSA infection, says the doctor head of the epidemiology center.
From the European Union there are strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also Hungary guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and disease images.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations are necessary so that no resistance to the agent can form, however, this directive of hospitals is not always observed.
Among the ambulants, or patients in basic care, microbiological samples are even less frequent, says Karolina Börökz.
Savings in the disinfection agents
Scientific evidence proves that MRSA is most often transferred from one patient to the other from the nursing staff.
This is why handwashing, or wearing gloves and masks has a significant importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient in domestic hospitals.
The rooms are even often overwhelmed, the beds are little ranked together, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters from an epidemiological point of view between them.
As Karolina Börökz continues to note, unfortunately, in the less financially well-established hospitals even comes to be saved in disinfection agents, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that just favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are proven much less common, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protection measures are observed, says Karolina Börökz.
Government programme against MRSA
To get MRSA infections in handle causes health insurance enormous costs, so they are fighted everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its restraint, was held in the government program.
After the first signs, the program is successful - as published data proves, the tendency of MRSA infections in England is decreasing.
The European Center for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant patogenes (including MRSA), as well as the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
