A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which have been housed at a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be viewed until now, unless with a humanitarian intent, i.e. individually and named, that is, on request of a former victim or his family.
The eleven states commissioned with their administration, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed to make them accessible to researchers and historians in May 2006.
After the ratification process of this Decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Heikle Information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable research, especially about the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the health status of forced workers, explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these named documents available to the public, due to the delicate character of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some deportation victims.
The prisoners lists of the concentration camps or the arrest orders issued by the Gestapo were collected after the war for a practical reason: finding civilians who were deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly providing proof of their arrest, in order to make them the way to their compensation.
Even today, in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 feast employees work out tens of thousands of personal requests.
However, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
Nothing fundamentally new in these documents should be expected, said Mr. Wolfgang Benz, Head of the Research Center for Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin, 2006.
