New concerns about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute shifted between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk that Russia’s exports of fuel to West Europe will be impaired.
The majority of Russian natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) is led by Ukraine and every dispute between the two nations is very closely observed.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia’s higher transit fees.
An earlier conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU states.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow happens at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be more calculated as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine must pay 40% more for the imports of Gazprom.
“It’s important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks,” Ukraine’s economic minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
“The changeing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] through Ukraine.”
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This consequently led to a case of exports to West Europe, which dramatically increased prices.
Russian gas makes up a quarter of the supply of the European Union.
Russia has the world’s largest gas stocks, but a lot of it remains underdeveloped.
The consequence is that Gazprom supplements its own stocks with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
