Climate on Venus could make a view of the future of the Earth
Venus was perhaps a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data of a European spacecraft on an orbit shows that the planet is even more similar to a default twin of the Earth than it had previously been aware of.
The Venus is the nearest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds have approximately the same size and have similar planetary railways, but the Venus is slightly closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, Venus would have dominated conditions that would have been very similar to those on earth and could have even been inhabitable, scientists believe today.
But because of the unbreaking carbon dioxide treehouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere through sunlight and a slower rotational pace, Venus introduced a completely different course of development.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-powerful winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the Venus Express Space Sound of the European Space Agency, which has examined the plants for a year, provide an enthusiastic view of how the Earth could develop in the face of catastrophic climate changes.
Professor Fred Taylor from the Physics Department at the University of Oxford, one of the heads of the Venus Express Mission, said: "It is clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that of Earth while the planets otherwise are pretty similar."
“Our new data allows us to build a scenario in which the Venus started billions of years ago like the Earth, possibly with an inhabitable environment.”
